        <p class="mb-3">
            <strong>Sorin Istrail</strong> is the James A. and Julie N. Brown Professor of Computational and Mathematical Sciences and Professor of Computer Science at <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://brown.edu">Brown University</a>, where he is a member of the <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.brown.edu/Research/Istrail_Lab/archive/CCMB/index.htm">Center for Computational Molecular Biology</a>. He is known for his foundational contributions to computational biology, statistical physics, and algorithms, including the proof of NP-completeness of the three-dimensional Ising model, central roles in the assembly of the human genome at Celera Genomics, and algorithmic work on haplotype assembly, gene regulatory networks, and protein folding.
        </p>

        <!-- Early Life -->
        <h2 id="early-life" class="text-xl font-bold border-b border-gray-300 pb-1 mt-6 mb-3">Early Life and Education</h2>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Sorin Istrail was born and raised in Târgu Neamț, Romania. He studied at the <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.uaic.ro/en/">Alexandru Ioan Cuza University</a> in Iași, one of Romania's oldest and most prestigious universities, where he developed early expertise in mathematics and theoretical computer science. He later received an honorary <em>Professor Honoris Causa</em> from this institution in 2010.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            His academic genealogy connects him to Euler in 9 links and to Leibniz in 11 links. He holds an Erdős number of 2 and a postcard-Erdős number of 1, reflecting personal scientific correspondence with Paul Erdős during his time at Sandia National Laboratories.
        </p>

        <!-- Career -->
        <h2 id="career" class="text-xl font-bold border-b border-gray-300 pb-1 mt-6 mb-3">Career</h2>

        <h3 id="sandia" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Sandia National Laboratories (1992–2000)</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Istrail founded and led the Computational Biology Project at <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.sandia.gov/">Sandia National Laboratories</a> from 1992 to 2000. During this period he made several important contributions spanning protein folding algorithms, physical mapping, and statistical physics. His most celebrated result from this era was the 2000 proof of the NP-completeness of the three-dimensional Ising model (see <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="#ising">below</a>), which was included among the Top 100 Most Important Discoveries of the U.S. Department of Energy's first 25 years.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Also during this period, Istrail served as General Chair of the inaugural <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.recomb.org/">RECOMB Conference</a> (Annual International Conference on Computational Molecular Biology), which he co-founded in 1997 alongside Pavel Pevzner and Michael Waterman.
        </p>

        <h3 id="celera" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Celera Genomics (2000–2005)</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            From 2000 to 2005, Istrail served as Senior Director and Head of Informatics Research at <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.celera.com/">Celera Genomics</a>, where his group played a central role in the computational assembly of the human genome. The resulting paper, <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.1058040">"The Sequence of the Human Genome"</a> (<em>Science</em>, 2001), has accumulated over 20,000 citations and is among the most cited scientific papers ever published.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            His group also developed genome-assembly-to-genome-assembly alignment algorithms used in <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0307971100">"Whole Genome Shotgun Assembly and Comparison of Human Genome Assemblies"</a> (<em>PNAS</em>, 2004). In 2002, his Celera team, in collaboration with ClearForrest, won the ACM KDD Cup—the premier international data mining competition—for automated annotation of a section of the <em>Drosophila</em> genome. In 2003 he was named an Applied Biosystems Science Fellow, one of only six scientists to hold that distinction in a company of 800 researchers.
        </p>

        <h3 id="brown" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Brown University (2005–present)</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Istrail joined Brown University in 2005 and was appointed the James A. and Julie N. Brown Professor of Computational and Mathematical Sciences in 2006. He served as the second Director of the <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://www.brown.edu/Research/Istrail_Lab/archive/CCMB/index.htm">Center for Computational Molecular Biology (CCMB)</a> from 2006 to 2011. He co-edited the <em>Journal of Computational Biology</em> as Co-Editor-in-Chief from 2000 to 2020, and co-edits the MIT Press Computational Molecular Biology series as well as the Springer-Verlag Lecture Notes in Bioinformatics series.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            At Brown, Istrail has continued research on SNPs and haplotypes, gene regulatory networks, protein folding algorithms, and the mathematical foundations of computational biology. He has trained dozens of PhD students, postdoctoral researchers, and undergraduate thesis students, many of whom now hold faculty or senior industry positions.
        </p>

        <!-- Research -->
        <h2 id="research" class="text-xl font-bold border-b border-gray-300 pb-1 mt-6 mb-3">Research</h2>

        <h3 id="ising" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">3D Ising Model and Statistical Physics</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            In 2000, Istrail published "Statistical Mechanics, Three-Dimensionality and NP-Completeness: I. Universality of Intractability of the Partition Functions of the Ising Model Across Non-Planar Lattices" (<em>STOC 2000</em>). The paper proved that for every non-planar crystal lattice—including every three-dimensional lattice—computing the partition function of the Ising model is NP-complete.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            The result resolved longstanding conjectures in statistical mechanics that had been open since the 1940s, including the Crossed-Bonds conjecture, and established that the methods of Onsager, Feynman, Kasteleyn, and others cannot be extended beyond planar lattices. The work was recognized as a Top 100 Discovery of the U.S. Department of Energy and as the 7th top achievement in Advanced Scientific Computing.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            The result is formalized by what Istrail calls the "universality equation": <em>Translational Invariance + Non-Planarity = Universality of NP-completeness</em>. In connection with this work, Brown University inaugurated the Ising-Onsager Distinguished Lecture Series, honoring both Lars Onsager (a former Brown professor and Nobel Laureate) and the legacy of this problem.
        </p>

        <h3 id="genomics" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Genomics and Genome Assembly</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            At Celera Genomics, Istrail's group contributed essential computational infrastructure for the whole-genome shotgun assembly of the human genome. Their algorithms addressed assembly, comparison, and alignment of genome-scale sequences. The comparative assembly work also contributed to the <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1133609">sea urchin genome</a> (<em>Science</em>, 2006) and the <a class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" href="https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1131898">transcriptome of the sea urchin embryo</a> (<em>Science</em>, 2006).
        </p>

        <h3 id="haplotypes" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">SNPs and Haplotype Assembly</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Istrail has made fundamental algorithmic contributions to the SNP haplotyping problem—reconstructing the two parental copies of a chromosome from sequencing reads. His group developed the <strong>HapCompass</strong> algorithm, which uses a cycle-basis graph model to assemble haplotypes with high accuracy from high-throughput sequencing data. Extensions addressed polyploid genomes, cancer genome haplotyping (HapCompass-Tumor), and identical-by-descent tract inference (Tractatus).
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            The foundational paper on this line of work, "SNPs Problems, Complexity and Algorithms" (ESA 2001, with Lancia, Bafna, Lippert, and Schwartz), received the European Symposium on Algorithms <strong>Test-of-Time Award</strong> in 2021.
        </p>

        <h3 id="regulatory" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Gene Regulatory Networks</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            In a 15-year collaboration with developmental biologist Eric H. Davidson (Caltech), Istrail developed computational frameworks for understanding the <em>genomic cis-regulatory code</em>—the logic by which transcription factor binding sites in DNA combinatorially control gene expression. Their joint work introduced Boolean logic models of cis-regulatory modules and gene regulatory networks (GRNs).
        </p>
        <p class="mb-3">
            This collaboration produced the <strong>cisGRN-Lexicon</strong>, a causality-inferred database of cis-regulatory architecture for over 600 transcription factor-encoding genes in eight species. Key papers include "Logic Functions of the Genomic cis-Regulatory Code" (<em>PNAS</em>, 2005) and "The Regulatory Genome and the Computer" (<em>Developmental Biology</em>, 2007).
        </p>

        <h3 id="protein" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">Protein Folding Algorithms</h3>
        <p class="mb-3">
            Istrail has contributed to the theory and algorithms of protein structure prediction, particularly within lattice models. With William Hart, he developed the first protein folding prediction algorithm with a provable approximation guarantee—achieving results within three-eighths of optimal in the hydrophobic-hydrophilic (HP) model on cubic lattices (<em>STOC</em> 1995, <em>Journal of Computational Biology</em> 1996). Other work addressed contact map overlap maximization for structure comparison using integer programming methods.
        </p>

